WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:03.120
Wes, have you seen this Airplane Mode box that you can put your phone in?

00:03.120 --> 00:07.760
I sure have. I don't know about you, Joe, but it's pretty difficult to stay away from my phone,

00:07.760 --> 00:12.400
even on the best of times. You're relaxing, you're at home, you're trying to have quality time with

00:12.400 --> 00:17.280
your friends or your family, and yet you're always drawn to the pocket. And that's where there's

00:17.280 --> 00:22.480
Airplane Mode, which, while it's a unique collaboration, so far it's just a prototype,

00:22.480 --> 00:28.400
but the designers really wanted to draw your attention to it. It's a concrete surface with

00:28.400 --> 00:32.720
some space inside for you to set your phone, and you really want to touch it. And as soon as you

00:32.720 --> 00:37.360
do, you quickly realize that opening the box requires both hands. It's a full sensorial

00:37.360 --> 00:42.480
experience. It's got a nice leather cradle. It's a special place for one of your mobile devices.

00:42.480 --> 00:47.200
You can put it inside, keep the vessel shut, and then now, next time you want it,

00:47.200 --> 00:50.320
it's an act of intention and not just being addicted.

00:50.320 --> 00:52.880
It does look like a giant bar of soap, though, doesn't it?

00:52.880 --> 00:57.280
Oh, you know, I hadn't even thought about that. Yes, it's either a really well-used pumice stone

00:57.280 --> 00:59.520
or a big dirty bar of soap.

00:59.520 --> 01:02.480
I don't know about you, but I've got the self-control to just not pick my phone up.

01:02.480 --> 01:06.080
I don't think I need to lock it in a big concrete container.

01:06.080 --> 01:11.680
Yeah, you know, I don't love the design. I am a little drawn to the intentionality and the idea

01:11.680 --> 01:17.520
that, well, maybe you have to choose to access your phone, but there is the lower tech solution,

01:17.520 --> 01:19.600
which is just turn your phone upside down.

01:19.600 --> 01:35.520
This is Linux Unplugged, episode 265, for September 4th, 2018.

01:37.680 --> 01:43.440
Welcome to Linux Unplugged, your weekly Linux talk show that's making a huge mess in the studio.

01:43.440 --> 01:46.000
