02:04.800 --> 02:08.640
We've got tons of community news, both the highs and the lows,

02:08.640 --> 02:14.000
plus an update from the Wild West of mobile Linux operating systems.

02:14.000 --> 02:18.560
Some Google, Microsoft, all those big names, they filter in here, too.

02:18.560 --> 02:22.960
And of course, the latest drama from some of the muckety-mucks of the Linux kernel.

02:22.960 --> 02:24.640
Plus, some of our picks rounds it out.

02:25.440 --> 02:28.960
I'm pretty excited, but before we can get to any of that great stuff,

02:28.960 --> 02:30.240
well, we're going to need some help.

02:30.240 --> 02:32.800
And I think I know just the crew.

02:32.800 --> 02:34.480
Time appropriate greetings, Mumble Room.

02:34.480 --> 02:35.120
Hello.

02:35.120 --> 02:39.840
Oh, listen to that. It makes my heart sigh with happiness every darn time.

02:39.840 --> 02:40.960
How are you guys today?

02:40.960 --> 02:41.280
Awesome.

02:41.280 --> 02:41.760
Good.

02:41.760 --> 02:42.880
Eating a steak.

02:42.880 --> 02:44.160
Eating a steak.

02:44.160 --> 02:47.200
Now you're just not focused here on Linux Unplugged.

02:47.200 --> 02:47.440
All right.

02:47.440 --> 02:50.080
Well, let's focus on the release of Linux Mint Debian Edition.

02:50.080 --> 02:52.240
LMDE 3 has been released.

02:52.240 --> 02:55.280
Yes, it sure has, codenamed Cindy.

02:55.280 --> 02:58.160
Now, if you're not really familiar with Linux Mint Debian Edition,

02:58.160 --> 03:00.160
it's just like the regular Linux Mint,

03:00.160 --> 03:04.080
but instead of having all of its base packages supplied from the Ubuntu distribution,

03:04.080 --> 03:08.160
well, they go back one level further and pull them straight from Debian.

03:08.160 --> 03:13.360
It's kind of a tracking project to keep the developers' minds at ease knowing that,

03:13.360 --> 03:17.920
well, if Ubuntu suddenly disappeared, Linux Mint would still have something to stand on.

03:17.920 --> 03:21.200
I know it was one of the distributions I first started out with.

03:21.200 --> 03:25.920
You know, obviously Ubuntu was right there at the beginning of my practical Linux career,

03:25.920 --> 03:27.920
but quickly after I was like, oh, what's this?

03:27.920 --> 03:31.280
What's this distribution that has all the media codecs pre-installed?

03:31.280 --> 03:37.760
And, you know, I do think Linux Mint does a reasonable job of having that user base in mind.

03:37.760 --> 03:38.960
You can see in the release notes,

03:38.960 --> 03:42.240
they've got just a section of common troubleshooting tips right off the bat.

03:42.240 --> 03:44.640
So if you're like, oh, my, you know, my DVDs won't play in VLC.

03:44.640 --> 03:45.120
What do I do?

03:45.120 --> 03:48.080
Well, they haven't fixed that, but they've at least thought about it enough

03:48.080 --> 03:51.600
to have a handy guide right at the same place that you download your ISO.

03:52.240 --> 03:56.480
A thing to keep in mind here, though, is there are no point releases for the Debian Edition.

03:56.480 --> 04:00.400
So you just get a big new rebase on the next Debian base,

04:00.400 --> 04:02.560
and then you'll get all the latest Linux Mint changes.

04:02.560 --> 04:04.720
They'll just filter on down to your system.

04:04.720 --> 04:06.800
But this time there's no Mate version then.

04:06.800 --> 04:08.160
No, there's not, Joe.

04:08.160 --> 04:09.520
And I don't know about you.

04:09.520 --> 04:13.200
I do like Cinnamon, but Mate has always been such a reliable choice.

04:13.200 --> 04:15.360
I wonder what the motivation for leaving it out?

04:15.360 --> 04:17.280
Well, you've got Ubuntu Mate now, of course,

04:17.280 --> 04:22.480
which kind of renders the Mate version of standard Linux Mint a little bit irrelevant.

04:22.480 --> 04:25.440
So maybe it's kind of an acknowledgement of that.

04:25.440 --> 04:27.680
You know, I could see that Linux Mint does.

04:27.680 --> 04:30.880
Cinnamon and Linux Mint seemed like they have a definite kinship.

04:30.880 --> 04:32.800
They're, you know, developed in parallel.

04:33.440 --> 04:36.720
I'm not sure if I would go with the Debian Edition over the Ubuntu Edition,

04:36.720 --> 04:38.000
just at the moment.

04:38.000 --> 04:40.400
But if you're a Debian fan, maybe you don't like all the things

04:40.400 --> 04:44.960
that Ubuntu layers on top of Ubuntu's philosophy of putting together a distribution.

04:44.960 --> 04:47.680
Well, hey, you've got options, Linux Mint fans.

04:47.680 --> 04:50.080
Now, I know that you love GNOME.

04:50.080 --> 04:52.080
I'm not the hugest fan of it,

04:52.080 --> 04:55.360
but you must be pretty hyped for 3.30 that's coming soon.

04:55.360 --> 04:56.640
3.30, I know.

04:56.640 --> 05:00.240
I think we're expecting sometime this week for that to drop.

05:00.240 --> 05:01.440
It'll be dropping this weekend.

05:01.440 --> 05:02.240
Perfect. Okay.

05:02.240 --> 05:06.240
Hey, that's something great to look forward to as we begin everyone getting back to work.

05:06.240 --> 05:08.320
Now that it's almost fall.

05:08.320 --> 05:12.000
And well, if you're getting back to work, maybe you're refreshing some of your systems.

05:12.000 --> 05:14.560
I would be looking forward to GNOME 3.30.

05:15.360 --> 05:19.120
And you can get a little preview of that by checking out the latest changes coming to

05:19.120 --> 05:20.160
GNOME Tweaks.

05:20.800 --> 05:22.480
Now, if you don't use GNOME Tweaks,

05:22.480 --> 05:25.520
just hearken back to the days before GNOME Tweaks was as good as it was,

05:25.520 --> 05:27.440
or really even available.

05:27.440 --> 05:31.520
And you'll realize that you probably had to go dig way deep into some settings

05:31.520 --> 05:34.080
and config files to make all these handy changes.

05:34.080 --> 05:37.280
Some of the changes that we're seeing is, well,

05:37.280 --> 05:40.400
to start off, there's volume indicators in GNOME 3.30,

05:40.400 --> 05:44.000
and they can indicate when over amplification is in use.

05:44.000 --> 05:48.400
Now I use over amplification all the time when I'm doing my noise removal.

05:48.400 --> 05:50.240
I have to turn up the volume way loud.

05:50.240 --> 05:53.920
So that would be handy because sometimes I come back having turned it way up,

05:53.920 --> 05:55.600
and that just blows my ears off.

05:55.600 --> 05:58.960
So if I knew there was this nice red line showing me that,

05:58.960 --> 06:02.400
then yeah, hopefully they can add that to XFCE at some point.

06:02.400 --> 06:06.400
Right? You can get that stuff, you know, it's buried in the ulcer or pulse settings,

06:06.400 --> 06:09.280
but having it right on the desktop really does make a bit of a difference.

06:09.920 --> 06:14.400
Now, there's another new setting here, and that's the sound theme selector.

06:15.120 --> 06:16.800
Sound themes aren't very popular yet,

06:16.800 --> 06:20.560
but maybe this will help them become just a bit more noticeable.

06:20.560 --> 06:22.800
But you have got sound themes in Ubuntu, haven't you, Popeye?

06:24.160 --> 06:28.720
Maybe. We had someone in the community make a sound theme many, many years ago,

06:28.720 --> 06:33.840
and we removed it. I think they were slowly removed.

06:33.840 --> 06:39.360
Like the one that played a sound when you logged out was removed because it was too long,

06:39.360 --> 06:43.360
because it turned out we could shut the system down before the song finished playing.

06:43.360 --> 06:47.040
And so it was seen, that was a bit daft, leaving it in there.

06:47.040 --> 06:49.600
And then slowly loads of the others have been removed as well.

06:49.600 --> 06:53.440
So most of the sound themes, I think, are removed.

06:53.440 --> 06:57.120
And the only thing you get is like a donk noise when you, you know,

06:57.120 --> 07:01.440
as the terminal bell, and there's not a lot of other noises in there.

07:01.440 --> 07:04.640
That's something, you know, I hadn't, I wasn't too familiar with sound themes

07:04.640 --> 07:06.400
even before researching for this show.

07:06.400 --> 07:09.040
So I'll be, I'll be playing with that in the future.

07:09.600 --> 07:12.720
One more thing I wanted to highlight was that coming up,

07:12.720 --> 07:17.440
we will see possibly center new windows, that option being enabled by default.

07:17.440 --> 07:21.520
And it doesn't sound like much, but actually, I think it's kind of a nice touch.

07:21.520 --> 07:24.160
Seems like it might be going into Ubuntu 18.10.

07:24.160 --> 07:26.720
Or it has been enabled in Ubuntu 18.10, rather.

07:27.280 --> 07:31.120
And that might be a setting I'm gonna have to copy on my custom assembled Gnome desktop.

07:31.760 --> 07:34.640
So it's not all good news this week, unfortunately, is it?

07:35.200 --> 07:38.880
Purism has pushed back the release date of the Librem 5

07:38.880 --> 07:42.560
in a shocking announcement that none of us saw coming.

07:42.560 --> 07:44.560
No, not ever.

07:45.440 --> 07:48.480
I am still, you know, just a little bit disappointed.

07:48.480 --> 07:51.360
It seems like you've been following this with some interest over there, Joe.

07:51.360 --> 07:52.880
Yeah, I've been following this from the start

07:52.880 --> 07:56.800
because I have wanted a totally free phone to be available,

07:56.800 --> 07:58.320
but I've also wanted it to be good.

07:58.880 --> 08:00.400
And that's kind of the problem.

08:00.880 --> 08:02.960
You know, when you're starting these things off from scratch,

08:02.960 --> 08:06.960
it's very difficult to make something that's going to even

08:07.920 --> 08:10.560
compete with iOS and Android in any way at all.

08:11.600 --> 08:14.000
It's interesting the spin that they put on this, though.

08:14.000 --> 08:18.960
The kind of official press release announcing this delay until April 2019

08:18.960 --> 08:24.560
is very much kind of laying on how great the idea is

08:24.560 --> 08:27.920
and, you know, how terrible the other alternatives are.

08:27.920 --> 08:29.360
And then it's kind of right at the bottom.

08:29.360 --> 08:30.960
Oh, yeah, and we've slipped a little bit.

08:31.520 --> 08:34.240
And here's a technical blog post for more details.

08:34.240 --> 08:37.360
And it's really that technical blog post that's more interesting

08:37.360 --> 08:40.240
talking about exactly why this delay has happened

08:40.240 --> 08:46.240
because they got this IMX 8 board later than they had planned, basically.

08:46.240 --> 08:47.600
And when they did their testing on it,

08:47.600 --> 08:50.960
it turns out that it wasn't quite up to scratch.

08:50.960 --> 08:52.400
Yeah, and, you know, there really just are.

08:52.400 --> 08:54.320
I think we've seen this from some of the other vendors

08:54.320 --> 08:55.760
who have attempted to play in this space.

08:55.760 --> 09:00.960
There's just a lot of challenges of making a non-Android-based mobile phone.

09:02.160 --> 09:04.160
Android has such a long and convoluted history,

09:04.160 --> 09:08.000
especially with all the intricacies you see on different systems on a chip

09:08.000 --> 09:11.280
and all the various blobs and other hardware components

09:11.280 --> 09:14.480
you need to assemble to make sure that it all boots up, can actually run.

09:14.480 --> 09:16.720
And then, as you so wisely put, Joe,

09:16.720 --> 09:20.240
you know, is actually usable at the end of the day.

09:20.240 --> 09:22.880
Yeah, unfortunately, the bugs in this case

09:23.440 --> 09:26.480
meant that it was just going to have terrible battery life

09:26.480 --> 09:28.320
and just it wouldn't go to sleep properly

09:28.320 --> 09:29.760
and use a single core, that sort of thing.

09:30.480 --> 09:32.640
So that's pretty critical.

09:32.640 --> 09:35.040
And at least they are acknowledging that and saying,

09:35.040 --> 09:36.560
look, we're going to have to delay it

09:36.560 --> 09:38.640
rather than just forging ahead and making it terrible.

09:39.440 --> 09:42.160
It kind of makes me think that once we finally do get this,

09:42.960 --> 09:44.240
it isn't going to be terrible.

09:44.240 --> 09:46.400
You know, they're putting some thought into this here.

09:46.400 --> 09:51.040
They're making sure that they don't just ship it as soon as they possibly can.

09:51.040 --> 09:52.160
They want it to be good.

09:53.200 --> 09:55.200
I mean, it's not going to compete with Android and iOS.

09:55.200 --> 09:57.920
There's just no doubt about that, not to start with.

09:57.920 --> 09:59.920
But it is going to be fully free.

09:59.920 --> 10:03.120
We have to hope that there is that sweet spot of usable enough

10:03.120 --> 10:06.400
and still respecting a lot of the principles and philosophical positions

10:06.400 --> 10:09.280
that I think a lot of the audience here is interested in

10:09.280 --> 10:12.800
and has just not been something that we've really been capable of

10:12.800 --> 10:15.120
barring maybe a few exceptions in the mobile space.

10:15.120 --> 10:17.520
Now, buried in those technical arguments, Joe,

10:17.520 --> 10:21.280
is there any mention of just how long it slipped?

10:21.280 --> 10:22.640
Well, yeah, they say April now.

10:22.640 --> 10:25.360
It was originally going to be January 2019.

10:25.360 --> 10:28.800
Now they're saying April, so pretty much a quarter,

10:28.800 --> 10:31.600
which sounds a bit arbitrary to me.

10:32.320 --> 10:35.760
I think that we'll be lucky to see it by the middle of next year, really,

10:35.760 --> 10:40.720
because, you know, they kind of had this plan to put it out in January,

10:40.720 --> 10:43.600
and it was all based on a certain number of things happening in a certain order,

10:43.600 --> 10:45.840
getting the development kits and all the rest of it.

10:45.840 --> 10:48.800
And each thing seems to be slipping just that little bit.

10:49.360 --> 10:54.240
So I think, yeah, we'll be lucky if it's before, I don't know, June or July.

10:54.240 --> 10:57.440
I'm not undecided on if I'm going to double down and keep playing on the Android world.

10:57.440 --> 11:02.000
I see those ever so smug and satisfied iPhone users and wonder,

11:02.000 --> 11:05.840
maybe in a world where I didn't use my phone for anything but simple phone things,

11:05.840 --> 11:07.040
that could work for me.

11:07.840 --> 11:11.280
There is, though, another option, and that's the Xero phone,

11:11.280 --> 11:16.080
which is a $50 open source smartphone based on the Raspberry Pi Zero.

11:16.080 --> 11:18.400
Yeah, this is a little bit speculative at the moment.

11:18.400 --> 11:19.760
It's not actually available.

11:19.760 --> 11:21.680
It's been announced on CrowdSupply,

11:21.680 --> 11:25.600
and you can kind of put your email address to register your interest.

11:25.600 --> 11:27.760
So who knows when it's actually going to come about?

11:27.760 --> 11:31.040
But it does look pretty cool that it's a very basic phone.

11:31.040 --> 11:34.560
What do you expect for $50 based on the Raspberry Pi Zero?

11:34.560 --> 11:37.680
But at least it is something a little bit different,

11:37.680 --> 11:41.360
and potentially that kind of second phone that you just take out

11:41.360 --> 11:43.600
when you don't really want to take your main phone out.

11:43.600 --> 11:45.600
Yeah, well, there's all kinds of use cases for that,

11:45.600 --> 11:49.600
even if it's just a backup phone because you smashed yours on a rock.

11:49.600 --> 11:52.400
It's kind of set apart by the things it doesn't have.

11:52.400 --> 11:55.120
No carrier locks, bloated apps, or data mining,

11:55.120 --> 11:57.680
and it doesn't depend on big companies.

11:58.240 --> 12:01.280
Of course, that means you lose out on plenty of other options,

12:01.280 --> 12:04.640
but I know I feel a little insecure when I just have the one phone,

12:04.640 --> 12:07.440
especially given how much you actually need to have.

12:07.440 --> 12:09.600
You need a phone to just communicate these days.

12:09.600 --> 12:13.280
So, hey, I have a Raspberry Pi Zero hanging around.

12:14.080 --> 12:16.240
Now it looks like I just need a few more supplies.

12:16.240 --> 12:18.320
Well, you definitely don't want to be using Android

12:18.320 --> 12:21.600
because Google will not patch a flaw

12:21.600 --> 12:25.600
in any of the other older versions of Android than the current one,

12:26.160 --> 12:27.920
which is pretty serious.

12:28.480 --> 12:29.360
Oh, Google.

12:31.040 --> 12:35.520
This is really exactly the sort of thing that makes people upset

12:35.520 --> 12:38.080
with modern phone and phone operating systems.

12:38.080 --> 12:39.840
Somewhere between all the different systems on a chip,

12:39.840 --> 12:43.280
somewhere between the rapid state of industry change,

12:43.280 --> 12:45.840
and then you have software practices.

12:45.840 --> 12:48.480
And that might be where it gets sometimes the most frustrating,

12:48.480 --> 12:52.000
at least for me, because you've got to imagine that this is possible,

12:52.000 --> 12:52.640
at least in theory.

12:52.640 --> 12:54.080
It may be that it's not profitable.

12:54.080 --> 12:57.360
It may be that it just is a lot of work to backport these patches.

12:58.400 --> 13:01.280
But come on, we know Google has the resources.

13:01.280 --> 13:04.160
Yeah, it's one thing for the vendors and the OEMs

13:04.160 --> 13:06.000
to not actually implement the patches,

13:06.000 --> 13:08.320
but for Google to just not put them out there in the first place,

13:08.320 --> 13:10.480
that's not very good, is it, at all, really?

13:10.480 --> 13:11.840
And to say to people,

13:12.400 --> 13:15.920
hey, here's your solution, upgrade to Android 9 Pie.

13:16.800 --> 13:17.840
What kind of solution is that

13:17.840 --> 13:20.720
when there's billions of people out there using the old versions?

13:20.720 --> 13:23.360
Yeah, I mean, it's not even really possible for anyone

13:23.360 --> 13:25.920
apart from those who use the Pixel devices,

13:25.920 --> 13:28.560
or if you're lucky enough that your manufacturer actually goes

13:28.560 --> 13:31.520
and updates whatever modified version they've based it on.

13:31.520 --> 13:33.440
Maybe you go install your own operating system,

13:33.440 --> 13:35.760
but you're pretty much a special case there.

13:35.760 --> 13:37.840
And what worries me is that there's going to be,

13:37.840 --> 13:38.960
you know, there's a lot of consumers

13:38.960 --> 13:40.640
who don't need the newest and greatest,

13:40.640 --> 13:42.800
and they have, some of my family members,

13:42.800 --> 13:44.960
they have the original Nexus 5.

13:44.960 --> 13:47.360
And while it's not fast and it doesn't have a lot of storage

13:47.360 --> 13:48.800
and the camera's not so great,

13:48.800 --> 13:50.960
it really does just work for them.

13:50.960 --> 13:53.760
But I worry knowing that they're on an unsupported platform

13:53.760 --> 13:55.680
that won't get security updates.

13:55.680 --> 14:00.080
And it's shocking that, you know, Android 9 just came out

14:00.080 --> 14:01.360
and that we're already in a world

14:01.360 --> 14:03.920
where anything else isn't secure.

14:03.920 --> 14:04.960
I don't like it.

14:04.960 --> 14:05.760
Yeah, I don't like it.

14:05.760 --> 14:07.600
But I like that you called me a special case, Wes,

14:07.600 --> 14:09.920
because, you know, I run Lineage on my phone,

14:09.920 --> 14:13.440
and my wife runs Lineage on her Nexus 5.

14:13.440 --> 14:15.120
So yeah, we're both special cases.

14:15.120 --> 14:16.080
I'm going to tell her that.

14:16.080 --> 14:19.600
Oh, how does the Lineage run on the Nexus 5?

14:19.600 --> 14:20.800
Has she been happy with that?

14:20.800 --> 14:23.040
Yeah, she's been very happy with it.

14:23.040 --> 14:24.960
The camera on that phone isn't great,

14:24.960 --> 14:26.320
and that's the only thing she doesn't like.

14:26.320 --> 14:29.600
But yeah, I keep trying to tell her to get,

14:29.600 --> 14:31.440
you know, trying to convince her to get a better phone

14:31.440 --> 14:32.560
just so I've got something to play with.

14:32.560 --> 14:34.400
But she says, no, I don't need to.

14:34.400 --> 14:34.800
It's fine.

14:34.800 --> 14:36.400
I've got security updates.

14:36.400 --> 14:38.240
It's working fine for what I need it for.

14:38.240 --> 14:38.800
It's small.

14:38.800 --> 14:40.640
